    <profileDesc>
      <abstract>
        <p>We propose a graph neural network architecture for sparse retrieval that
        combines message passing with attention pooling. Our method improves
        recall over strong baselines while remaining efficient on CPU-only
        hardware.</p>
      </abstract>
    </profileDesc>
  </teiHeader>
  <text xml:lang="en">
    <body>
      <div>
        <head>1 Introduction</head>
        <p>Graph Neural Network (GNN) models have become a standard tool for
        learning over relational data <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1]</ref>.
        Prior work has explored message passing schemes extensively
        <ref type="bibr" target="#b1">[2]</ref>, but efficient sparse
        retrieval remains challenging.</p>
        <div>
          <head>Related Work</head>
          <p>Several approaches combine attention with graph structure
          <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1]</ref>, though most assume dense
          adjacency and do not scale to the sparse setting we target.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <head>2 Method</head>
        <p>Figure 1 illustrates the overall pipeline described below.</p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_0">
          <head>Figure 1 :</head>
          <label>1</label>
          <figDesc>Figure 1: Overview of the attention-pooled message passing pipeline.</figDesc>
          <graphic coords="1,72.00,178.57,319.30,220.00" type="bitmap"/>
        </figure>
        <p>We first embed each node independently, then apply attention-weighted
        message passing over the graph neighborhood.</p>
      </div>
